## 4. PROP DRILLING SOLUTIONS

When props pass through 3+ levels, it's a smell. Fix with one of these approaches, in order of preference:

### Option A — Composition (best for most cases)
Move the consuming component up and pass it as `children` or a render prop:

```tsx
// BEFORE: drilling `user` through 3 levels
function Page() {
  const user = useUser();
  return <Layout user={user}><Sidebar user={user}><Avatar user={user} /></Sidebar></Layout>;
}

// AFTER: compose at the top, no drilling
function Page() {
  const user = useUser();
  return (
    <Layout sidebar={<Sidebar avatar={<Avatar user={user} />} />}>
      <MainContent />
    </Layout>
  );
}
```

### Option B — Context (for truly shared state)
Only when the same data is needed by many components at different depths:

```tsx
// contexts/UserContext.tsx
const UserContext = createContext<User | null>(null);

export function UserProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const user = useUser(); // hook that fetches user
  return <UserContext.Provider value={user}>{children}</UserContext.Provider>;
}

export function useCurrentUser(): User {
  const user = useContext(UserContext);
  if (!user) throw new Error('useCurrentUser must be used within UserProvider');
  return user;
}
```

**Context rules:**
- One context per domain concept (UserContext, ThemeContext, etc.) — not one giant AppContext
- Context value should be stable — memoize with `useMemo` if it's an object
- Never put rapidly-changing state in context (mouse position, scroll offset) — it rerenders all consumers

### Option C — Custom hook accessing shared store
For complex state (many actions, many consumers), use Zustand, Jotai, or Redux Toolkit:

```tsx
// stores/useUserStore.ts (Zustand example)
import { create } from 'zustand';

interface UserStore {
  user: User | null;
  isLoading: boolean;
  fetchUser: () => Promise<void>;
}

export const useUserStore = create<UserStore>((set) => ({
  user: null,
  isLoading: true,
  fetchUser: async () => {
    set({ isLoading: true });
    const user = await fetch('/api/me').then(r => r.json());
    set({ user, isLoading: false });
  },
}));
```

---

## 5. COMPONENT CATEGORIES

Every component should fall into one of these categories. If it doesn't, it's trying to do too much.

### Presentational (pure display)
- Receives data via props
- No side effects, no fetch calls, no direct state mutations
- Same props → same output, always
- Easy to test: render with props, assert output

```tsx
interface MetricCardProps {
  label: string;
  value: string;
  trend?: { direction: 'up' | 'down'; value: string };
}

function MetricCard({ label, value, trend }: MetricCardProps) {
  return (
    <div style={{
      padding: 'var(--space-6)',
      borderRadius: 'var(--radius-lg)',
      border: '1px solid var(--color-border)',
    }}>
      <p style={{ fontSize: 'var(--text-xs)', color: 'var(--color-text-secondary)', fontWeight: 500 }}>
        {label}
      </p>
      <p style={{ fontSize: 'var(--text-2xl)', fontWeight: 600, marginTop: 'var(--space-1)' }}>
        {value}
      </p>
      {trend && (
        <span style={{
          fontSize: 'var(--text-xs)',
          color: trend.direction === 'up' ? 'var(--color-success)' : 'var(--color-error)',
          fontWeight: 500,
        }}>
          {trend.direction === 'up' ? '↑' : '↓'} {trend.value}
        </span>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Container (data + orchestration)
- Fetches data via hooks
- Manages loading/error/empty states
- Passes data down to presentational children
- Minimal JSX — mostly wiring

### Layout
- Defines spatial arrangement: grid, flex, sidebar, stack
- No data fetching, no business logic
- Receives children via `children` prop or named slots

### Interactive (user input)
- Controlled: state lives in parent, component receives `value` + `onChange`
- Self-contained event handling for local concerns (toggling a dropdown)
- Form inputs, buttons, selectors, toggles

---

## 6. NAMING CONVENTIONS

- Name by **what it is**, not what data it shows: `MetricCard` not `RevenueDisplay`
- Container suffixes: `Dashboard`, `Page`, `Screen`, `Panel`
- Presentational suffixes: `Card`, `Row`, `Item`, `Badge`, `Avatar`
- Layout suffixes: `Layout`, `Grid`, `Stack`, `Sidebar`
- Hook prefix: `use` — always: `useUsers`, `useDashboardData`, `useFilteredUsers`
- Utility files: lowercase, descriptive: `formatters.ts`, `validators.ts`, `api.ts`

---

## 7. FILE STRUCTURE

Organize by feature, not by type:

```
src/
├── features/
│   ├── dashboard/
│   │   ├── Dashboard.tsx           ← container
│   │   ├── DashboardSkeleton.tsx   ← loading state
│   │   ├── MetricsRow.tsx          ← presentational
│   │   ├── hooks/
│   │   │   ├── useDashboardData.ts
│   │   │   └── useFilteredUsers.ts
│   │   └── __tests__/
│   │       └── Dashboard.test.tsx
│   ├── users/
│   │   ├── UserList.tsx
│   │   ├── UserCard.tsx
│   │   └── hooks/
│   │       └── useUsers.ts
├── components/                     ← shared components
│   ├── ErrorState.tsx
│   ├── EmptyState.tsx
│   ├── Skeleton.tsx
│   ├── FadeIn.tsx
│   └── ErrorBoundary.tsx
├── hooks/                          ← shared hooks
│   └── useMediaQuery.ts
├── utils/                          ← shared utilities
│   ├── formatters.ts
│   └── validators.ts
```

If the project already has a different structure, **match it**. Don't reorganize the whole codebase in one session. But when creating new files, steer toward feature-based organization.
